1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:17,000
We've talked about how we can identify ourselves to a system.

2
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:20,000
We've talked about how we authenticate ourselves to a system.

3
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:37,000
We've talked about how we can identify ourselves to a system.

4
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:40,000
We've talked about how we authenticate ourselves to a system

5
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:44,000
through authentication by knowledge, ownership, or characteristic.

6
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:47,000
Now, let's talk about how we authorize.

7
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:50,000
How the system determines what our access will be.

8
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:55,000
There's three major philosophies for authorization.

9
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:59,000
The first is known as discretionary access control.

10
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:01,000
And listen very carefully to this definition.

11
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:06,000
Discretionary access control means that the owner decides

12
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:09,000
who's going to get access to the system.

13
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:14,000
Now, is that a good security practice for the owner decides who should get access?

14
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:16,000
Absolutely.

15
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:18,000
Is that commonly what's done?

16
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:20,000
Unfortunately not.

17
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:23,000
It's very common that it's not the owner that decides who gets access.

18
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:28,000
Instead, it's someone an IT or some other system administrator like that.

19
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:30,000
And they're not the owner of the system.

20
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:35,000
So the perfect definition of discretionary access means the owner decides.

21
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:39,000
And there's three types of discretionary access that you need to know about.

22
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:44,000
There is rule-based, role-based, and attribute-based.

23
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:47,000
And we'll talk through each of those in more detail in a moment.

24
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:52,000
The next access control philosophy is non-disgressionary.

25
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:57,000
So if discretionary means the owner decides what does non-disgressionary mean?

26
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:01,000
Well, it means someone other than the owner decides.

27
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:05,000
And as I mentioned, that's very common in the world today in a lot of organizations,

28
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:07,000
but not a good practice.

29
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:11,000
The final philosophy is what's known as mandatory access control.

30
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:15,000
And this is where the system decides.

31
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:17,000
This is very rarely seen.

32
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:21,000
And we'll talk about it in a few minutes here, but it's very rare to see mandatory access control.

33
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:27,000
The two that you'll see the most out in the real world are discretionary and non-disgressionary.

34
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:29,000
So let's dig into each of these.

35
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:34,000
Now, relating this back to the reference monitor concepts and security kernels,

36
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:41,000
what these authorization steps are all about is determining the rules that get fed into our mediation.

37
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:48,000
And as we talked about in discretionary access, it's the owner that determines these rules.

38
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:53,000
Now, role-based access is where we have this concept of defining roles

39
00:02:53,000 --> 00:02:58,000
and then assigning users to those roles, which defines what access they get.

40
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:06,000
And role-based access can be an awesome idea in situations where you've got a ton of users that all share the same role.

41
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:07,000
Think call centers.

42
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:09,000
You might have 500 people in a call center.

43
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:11,000
They all need the same system access.

44
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:16,000
So you define one role, assign all 500 employees to that one role.

45
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:21,000
And then if you need to make changes to their access, you only have to update one role.

46
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:23,000
Makes this very easy.

47
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Now, in my experience, it's often challenging to implement role-based access across the entire organization.

48
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:37,000
I've been involved in a number of these implementations, and it's not uncommon to end up with more roles than you have employees,

49
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:40,000
which kind of negates making this whole process more efficient.

50
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:45,000
The other challenge a lot of organizations have is that many systems don't support role-based access, older legacy systems.

51
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:48,000
So role-based access create idea.

52
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:50,000
Not always easy to accomplish.

53
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:55,000
Rule-based access is where a simple set of rules.

54
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:58,000
Often, these are known as accles, access control lists.

55
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:03,000
It's simply a file that says this user has access to this resource or this asset.

56
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:06,000
So rule-based access is simply a set of rules.

57
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:09,000
And those rules are going to be unique to each user.

58
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:16,000
And so if you need to update 10 users access, you'd have to go and update their 10 unique rule sets.

59
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:21,000
Let's talk about an emerging form of access.

60
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:23,000
And it's known as attribute-based access.

61
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:27,000
And to give a bit of context as to why this is really useful and important nowadays,

62
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:31,000
let's talk about where the industry is trending as it comes to access to systems,

63
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:35,000
and what type of systems are being created, and where those systems are hosted.

64
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:41,000
So nowadays, it's very common for most applications to be web-based applications.

65
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:45,000
And for a lot of those applications to be hosted in the cloud,

66
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:47,000
which we call software as a service.

67
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:52,000
Now, if you have an application hosted in the cloud as software as a service,

68
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:56,000
all of the defense and depth controls that you would have used to have had

69
00:04:56,000 --> 00:04:59,000
when that application was deep within your corporate resources,

70
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:02,000
or deep within your corporate network, they're gone.

71
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:07,000
You know, it used to be very common that applications were hosted inside a company's own IT infrastructure.

72
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:11,000
And there was multiple layers of defense, firewalls, and all sorts of other controls

73
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:16,000
that would prevent unauthorized users from getting near that secure internal system.

74
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:21,000
But when we host the system in the cloud, who can access this system?

75
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:23,000
Potentially anyone on the internet.

76
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:28,000
And this is where the idea of attribute-based access becomes much more important.

77
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:32,000
Because the idea here is when we put a system out on the internet,

78
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:34,000
all those defense and depth controls are now gone.

79
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:36,000
We don't have those controls in place.

80
00:05:36,000 --> 00:05:40,000
And so the access controls, the controls that we use to control access to the application,

81
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:43,000
become much, much more important.

82
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:46,000
And attribute-based access really takes that into account.

83
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:51,000
Because the idea behind attribute-based access is rather than just looking at a simple user name and password

84
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:54,000
to grant someone access, and authorize what they're allowed to access,

85
00:05:55,000 --> 00:06:00,000
instead you look at a bunch of attributes such as you could look at the user

86
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:04,000
and specifically what's their identity, what department do they work in,

87
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:06,000
what date and time are they logging in from.

88
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:10,000
You could look at what environment they're logging in from.

89
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:14,000
Are they using, for instance, a Linux system and everyone in the company is being issued

90
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:16,000
Macs or Windows computers.

91
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:19,000
You could look at the operating system they're running.

92
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:21,000
You could look at even at their geographic location.

93
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:24,000
A lot of devices nowadays have GPS on board,

94
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:27,000
so you can see someone's fairly accurate latitude and longitude.

95
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:31,000
And if they're trying to log in from somewhere sketchy like, say, Canada,

96
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:33,000
that's going to look instantly suspicious.

97
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:37,000
You could look at what resources they're wanting to actually access.

98
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:39,000
Is this top-secret documents?

99
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:45,000
Is it, you know, is it an entire database or just a file?

100
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:48,000
And you could even look at what exactly do they want to do?

101
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:50,000
Do they want to read the file?

102
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:52,000
Do they want to download the entire thing?

103
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:54,000
Do they want to modify it?

104
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:57,000
So you can look at all these different attributes and then,

105
00:06:57,000 --> 00:07:00,000
based on all this, you can make an authorization decision.

106
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:04,000
And the way that we make these authorization decisions is based on a set of policy,

107
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:05,000
some logic.

108
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:08,000
It's basically a set of rules that we program into our authorization engine

109
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:13,000
so that it then can make a determination as to permit or deny certain actions,

110
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:15,000
looking at all these different attributes.

111
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:18,000
So that's the idea behind attribute-based access.

112
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:21,000
And I'll bet a lot of you have actually seen an example of this recently.

113
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:25,000
Now, these policies that we use to program our authorization engine,

114
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:28,000
the language that we use that we write these policy statements in,

115
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:33,000
is known as XACML, the Extensible Access Control Markup Language.

116
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:38,000
So just remember that as the language that we use to write the policies in,

117
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:40,000
attribute-based access.

118
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:44,000
And you might think attribute-based access is this super rare thing

119
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:47,000
I've never seen before, but I would bet every single one of you have seen it.

120
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:49,000
And here's a perfect example.

121
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:53,000
You've probably logged into a website recently where you had to click a box that said,

122
00:07:53,000 --> 00:07:54,000
I'm not a robot.

123
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:58,000
How does clicking a box prove that you're not a robot?

124
00:07:58,000 --> 00:08:01,000
Well, what's going on behind the scenes is that Google,

125
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:05,000
who runs this recapture system, is looking at a whole bunch of different attributes

126
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:07,000
when you try and click that box.

127
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:10,000
They're looking at the IP address that you're coming from,

128
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:13,000
the type of system you're on, how many times you've tried to click on that box

129
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:14,000
in the last few minutes.

130
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:18,000
And importantly, they're looking at how you click on that box.

131
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:21,000
If you were a robot, you'd probably go right to the center of the box,

132
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:23,000
click dead center, it'd be very mechanical.

133
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:27,000
If you're a human, you'd probably drunkenly stagger up to the box,

134
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:29,000
barely get the edge of it.

135
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:30,000
It would look very different.

136
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:34,000
And so this whole, I'm not a robot, is looking at all these different attributes

137
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:37,000
to decide whether you're a robot or not.

138
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:39,000
Okay, this next little bit, not an exam,

139
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:41,000
but I think it's a really fun little bit of trivia.

140
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:43,000
That's quite interesting to know.

141
00:08:43,000 --> 00:08:46,000
So the system before, I'm not a robot checkbox,

142
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:48,000
used to be this capture system,

143
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:52,000
where you had to type in this horribly scrambled and mangled text.

144
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:54,000
Where did that text come from?

145
00:08:54,000 --> 00:08:57,000
For many years, where a lot of that text came from,

146
00:08:57,000 --> 00:09:00,000
was from the Google book scanning project.

147
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:02,000
Google had a, and they think they stole or doing it,

148
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:06,000
they had a project where they were trying to scan all the world's old books

149
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:09,000
so that they could put them online and make them searchable.

150
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:11,000
Great idea.

151
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:15,000
The problem was that a lot of these books being very old and kind of rough shape

152
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:18,000
were very difficult for the OCR, the optical character recognition software

153
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:20,000
to actually figure out what the letters were.

154
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:23,000
And so what Google did is they got millions of us all around the world

155
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:25,000
to translate these books for them.

156
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:27,000
They would take these mangled bits of text,

157
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:29,000
they put them in these captures,

158
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:31,000
and then we would type in what we thought the characters were.

159
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:34,000
And if enough of us said, oh yeah, that's a B, or that's a J,

160
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:36,000
then the system would go, okay, yeah, that's the letter,

161
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:38,000
and that's how the recapture system worked.

162
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:40,000
So that's where the letters came from.

163
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:42,000
Where did some of the numbers come from?

164
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:46,000
Well, for a while there, Google was sourcing the numbers

165
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:48,000
from their street view project.

166
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:50,000
Google has been driving cars all around the world,

167
00:09:50,000 --> 00:09:53,000
taking pictures of all the world's streets, and capturing house numbers.

168
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:56,000
And they wanted to be able to tie a particular picture of a house

169
00:09:56,000 --> 00:09:59,000
to that house number so that when you typed in a address,

170
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:01,000
they could show you the exact house.

171
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:04,000
And in some instances, the pictures captured of the house numbers

172
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:06,000
were tough for the computer system to translate.

173
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:08,000
And so, what do they do?

174
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:11,000
They put those numbers into the recapture system.

175
00:10:11,000 --> 00:10:16,000
And millions of us around the world entered what we thought those numbers were,

176
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:20,000
trained Google's system on how to recognize those numbers and those letters.

177
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:22,000
So that's kind of where that came from.

178
00:10:22,000 --> 00:10:25,000
Now, one final piece here that's, I think, really cool.

179
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:27,000
In the new, I'm not a robot system.

180
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:29,000
It makes a bit of a risk-based decision.

181
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:32,000
If it's not entirely sure whether you're a robot or not,

182
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:34,000
it'll actually show you a grid of pictures,

183
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:36,000
a three-by-three grid of pictures.

184
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:38,000
And when the system was first put out there,

185
00:10:38,000 --> 00:10:40,000
it was usually pictures of kittens and bunnies.

186
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:43,000
And they'd ask you to, like, which of the puppies here or which of the kittens?

187
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:47,000
But now, when you get those grid of pictures, what are most of the pictures?

188
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:50,000
There's street signs, there's school buses, things like that.

189
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:52,000
Because what are you training now?

190
00:10:52,000 --> 00:10:55,000
You're training Google's self-driving cars. They're Waymo cars.

191
00:10:55,000 --> 00:10:59,000
So, Google's been very good at figuring out how to get all of us around the world

192
00:10:59,000 --> 00:11:03,000
to work for free to train their machine learning algorithms.

193
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:08,000
Now, the next type of authorization is mandatory access control.

194
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:10,000
And we have to spend a minute on this one.

195
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:12,000
As I want to explain something important,

196
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:16,000
mandatory access control is very, very rare to see.

197
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:17,000
Here's why.

198
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:20,000
In order to have mandatory access control,

199
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:24,000
every single asset in the organization has to have a classification.

200
00:11:24,000 --> 00:11:28,000
And every single user has to have some sort of security clearance.

201
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:32,000
Because the system has to decide who's going to get access to what,

202
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:33,000
based on all this.

203
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:38,000
And it's very rare for organizations to have classified all of their assets

204
00:11:38,000 --> 00:11:41,000
and to have security clearance and classified all of their users.

205
00:11:41,000 --> 00:11:46,000
So, it's very rare to see mandatory access control outside of US military

206
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:48,000
and other governmental types of organizations.

207
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:50,000
So, I'd warn you on the exam.

208
00:11:50,000 --> 00:11:54,000
Mandatory access control is very rarely the right answer.

209
00:11:54,000 --> 00:11:58,000
Because you almost never see it in the real world.

210
00:11:58,000 --> 00:12:02,000
And an important part that you might see on the exam related to mandatory access control

211
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:04,000
is that it requires labeling.

212
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:09,000
We have to label our data so that the system can decide who gets access to what.

213
00:12:09,000 --> 00:12:14,000
The final authorization philosophy is non-discretionary.

214
00:12:14,000 --> 00:12:17,000
And non-discretionary means who determines the rules?

215
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:19,000
Not the owner.

216
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:21,000
Someone from IT or something like that.

217
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:22,000
So, there you go.

218
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:25,000
Those are the major access control philosophies.

219
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:37,000
Music

